column9: There was far too much unstructured time and ‚Äúfluff‚Äù in this program. We were often left on our own to ‚Äúwork on a project,‚Äù which felt unrealistic given that we were expected to learn new tools and implement a solution by the end of day three.  After the first day, there was minimal hands‚Äëon use of the technology. Most of the remaining time focused on abstract discussions about ‚Äúbeing human‚Äù or other theoretical ideas rather than practical skill‚Äëbuilding. Additionally, the tracks were not well‚Äëdefined‚Äîparticipants who fell between the Developer and Productivity paths had no clear way to succeed in either.  Overall, the structure made it difficult to gain meaningful experience with the tools or achieve the intended outcomes.
column11: I think the experience would be greatly improved with more intentional structure and actionable content. Consider creating tracks that align with participant goals and backgrounds‚Äîsuch as entrepreneurs, educators, and tech/computer specialists‚Äîso attendees can dive into material that is actually relevant to how they plan to use the tools.  The sessions should focus more on action: walking us step‚Äëby‚Äëstep through how to use each tool, set up programs correctly, and maximize their inner workings. Demonstrating these processes in detail would make the learning tangible and applicable.  Soft‚Äëskill and ‚Äúhuman‚Äù conversations are valuable but should be limited to one dedicated session, rather than spread throughout. Much of the time felt dominated by buzzwords and abstract, ‚Äúimpactful‚Äësounding‚Äù discussions without concrete takeaways. A shift toward hands‚Äëon, practical instruction would make the program far more effective.
